From Mark Pundurs Subject Re After years can we say that Christian Morality is In mathew writes There's no objective physics Einstein and Bohr have told us Speaking as one who knows relativity and quantum mechanics I say There's no objective LSD should be sufficient to prove Speaking as one who has taken LSD I say One wonders just what people who ask such questions understand by the term objective if I consider it to be a useful fiction an abstract ideal we can strive Like an ideal gas or a light inextensible string it doesn't actually exist but we can talk about things as if they were like it and not be too far How could striving toward an ideal be in any way useful if the ideal had no objective existence Mark Pundurs any resemblance between my opinions and those of Wolfram Research is purely coincidental